According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global Busbar-free (0BB) Stringer Market was valued at USD 26.1 million in 2024 and is projected to reach USD 294 million by 2032, expanding at a robust CAGR of 16.5% during the forecast period. The market is witnessing rapid growth as photovoltaic manufacturers increasingly adopt busbar-free interconnection technologies to improve solar module efficiency, reduce silver consumption, and enhance production economics. The transition toward next-generation solar cell architectures such as TOPCon, HJT, and back-contact cells continues to strengthen demand for advanced 0BB stringer equipment worldwide.
The market is benefiting from the global shift toward renewable energy and the growing emphasis on manufacturing high-efficiency photovoltaic modules. Busbar-free (0BB) stringers eliminate traditional main busbars and rely on multiple ultra-fine wires to interconnect solar cells, reducing shading losses while improving light absorption and electrical performance. In addition to increasing module conversion efficiency, the technology significantly lowers silver paste consumption, enabling manufacturers to reduce production costs while meeting evolving industry performance standards.
